<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Alfonse </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON>'s hometown on <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> will return $ 1 million in <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> funds that were earmarked to build a swimming pool, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported. Island Park officials requested earlier this week that their application for the pool be withdrawn, citing local opposition to the project and rising costs, the Times reported in its Saturday editions. The officials denied that the cancellation was spurred by a federal inquiry into HUD-sponsored projects on <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, including in <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, the Times said. Island Park was awarded the $ 1 million in grants for the pool last year after <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON>, a village resident, personally lobbied then-HUD Secretary <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>, the Times said. The money for the pool came from <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>'s discretionary fund. In a letter to village residents last fall, <PERSON> DAmato </PERSON> praised <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>'s `` wise decision to approve this grant,'' the Times reported The pool was to have been built near a beach. An assistant to <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> secretary <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> said <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> was pleased the pool project was dead. `` We think the funds can be used for a purpose that will be more in line with assisting low-income individuals,'' <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Brunette </PERSON>, the assistant, told the Times. The Times said it got no answer to telephone calls made to <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON>'s office Friday afternoon. In <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, investigators are looking into allegations that HUD-sponsored houses went to politically connected residents instead of to minorities, as had been planned.
