<HEAD>Police Renew Mass Gang Sweeps on Eve of July Fourth Holiday Weekend</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `Police made ..., to UPDATE arrest totals, restore
dropped first reference for Detective Tony Celli.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH COTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police swarmed through gang-infested neighborhoods Friday night in the first widespread dragnet for drug-dealing street thugs since the highly-publicized sweeps dubbed the `` Hammer'' last summer. The eight-hour operation on the eve of the July Fourth holiday weekend targeted gangs in the three neighborhoods terrorized by gangs. Assistant Chief <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Vernon </PERSON> told 300 officers at a 4 p.m. roll call that they should remember many residents are law-abiding citizens. Portable booking trailers were set up at the Police Department's Southeast Division station in the heart of the <LOCATION> Watts </LOCATION> district which was ravaged by riots in 1965 Police made 70 arrests in the first four hours of the operation, 30 of them narcotics felonies, and 19 of those arrested were identified as gang members, said police Detective <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Celli </PERSON>. Twenty vehicles lacking current registration tags were impounded, he said. `` We are here to enforce all the laws that are applicable,'' said <PERSON> Celli </PERSON>. Community outcry over gang thugs who keep residents prisoners in their own homes prompted the first full-scale police assault in April 1988. The 1,000-officer weekend sweeps continued at intervals through the summer. Mayor <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>, a former police lieutenant sworn to a fifth term Friday, vowed during the first of the 1,000-officer gang task force sweeps 15 months ago: `` We are going to take these terrorists off the streets of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>.'' Gang violence continued unabated. More than one person died in a county gang-related killing for every day of 1988. There were 452 gang-related slayings in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> in 1988, surpassing the 387 gang-related murders reported the year before.
