<HEAD>Computer Art Exhibit Opens at Computer Museum</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Neon and videotape have replaced oils and watercolors at an art exhibit devoted exclusively to computers. More than 50 works by computer artists from around the world went on display Friday at The Computer Museum. The art, including two - and three - dimensional works, kinetic sculpture, animation and poly-dimensional works on videotape, runs until Among the works: the 144 neon lights that form <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> artist <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> X. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hauser </PERSON>'s `` wall-o-fish'' and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> artist <PERSON> Lillian </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwartz </PERSON>'s chrome-plated mobile `` Capricious Constellation.'' `` The one thing all these pieces have in common is that they've been created by both humans and computers,'' said museum spokeswoman <PERSON> Gail </PERSON> <PERSON> Jennes </PERSON> The exhibit titled `` Computer Art in Context'' is part of a conference on computer graphics sponsored by <LOCATION> Siggraph </LOCATION>, one of the world's leading professional associations of computer graphics researchers and practitioners. <PERSON> Hauser </PERSON>, 34, a glass blower by trade, arranged his neon work with the use of a computer that controls the lighting and shape of the design. <PERSON> Schwartz </PERSON> designed her giant mobile `` Capricious Constellation'' with the help of scientist <PERSON> Arno </PERSON> <PERSON> Penzias </PERSON>, who won the Nobel Prize for physics in 1978. The mobile is driven by a computer programmed to move it at random as if blown by winds. The Computer Museum officials say theirs is the only museum in the world devoted exclusively to computers and their impact on society. It includes 60 permanent exhibits, an animation theater and a multimedia robot show.
