<FIRST>r a PM-JunkDispute     07-01 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Junk Dispute,0418</SECOND>
<HEAD>Elderly Woman Fights City in Dispute Over Can Collecting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Honey <PERSON> Breske </PERSON> is trying to make ends meet by recycling, but prosecutors have taken the 92-year-old widow to court over the pile of trash in her yard. Now she is looking for a job to earn the money for the court battle. `` Spry ... widow seeking any employment,'' her advertisement reads. `` Need funds to fight Housing Court. They wo n't let me recycle cans for cash.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Breske </PERSON> placed the ad in a weekly newspaper after the city went to court to force her to clear debris from her yard, where she keeps aluminum cans, boxes and other junk she recycles to supplement her $ 369 monthy Social Security income. Her neighbors complained about the mess. `` I do n't think it's fair. These things did n't happen until our husbands died,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Breske </PERSON> said. `` Then they started picking on us.'' One of Mrs. <PERSON> Breske </PERSON>'s friends, <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunlap </PERSON>, is in trouble with the city for the same reason. The court has issued a permanent injunction against storing debris in her yard and issued more than $ 10,000 in fines over the last 12 years. `` I ca n't pay nothing,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Dunlap </PERSON>, 70. City attorneys handling such cases say many elderly residents are turning up in Housing Court, accused of creating dangerous piles of refuse in attempts to earn money. `` We have one to two cases every week with this type of problem,'' said <PERSON> Dolores </PERSON> <PERSON> Quiroz </PERSON>, the assistant corporation counsel prosecuting Mrs. <PERSON> Breske </PERSON>. `` And that's a conservative estimate. Sometimes it's one or two a day.'' The city gets involved in cases where debris poses possible fire and health hazards. `` It was not just a matter of cans and things like that,'' she said. `` The problem is that they keep collecting it, and it's causing serious problems with the neighbors. Mrs. <PERSON> Breske </PERSON> finds recyclable items by rummaging through alleys in her neighborhood. She started collecting about 10 years ago just after her husband, <PERSON> Harry </PERSON>, was hospitalized for a heart attack. He died five years later, leaving Mrs. <PERSON> Breske </PERSON> with a $ 45,000 hospital bill. She emptied her bank account and sold jewelry to help pay it. `` I went looking for a job a couple of times. When I told them my age, they said, ` What do you want to work for?''' she said. `` So I got tired of that. I said, ` I'll just go pick cans.'''
