<TEXT>
 Police arrested at least seven striking <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> pilots and employees Friday as they stopped their cars in a baggage area at <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>'s big airport on one of its busiest days. `` It is a grassroots movement,'' said <PERSON> Hank </PERSON> <PERSON> Weber </PERSON>, a spokesman for the Eastern pilots union in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>. `` Some disgruntled Eastern strikers, including non-union people, are trying to show their frustration.'' Those arrested were charged with misdemeanors _ disobeying an officer and impeding the flow of traffic _ and nearly all of the arrested were pulled from cars at an Eastern baggage area at <LOCATION> Hartsfield-Atlanta </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>. Other strikers gathered signatures on petitions that called for a continued boycott of the airline, which has been crippled by a four-month strike. `` We asked them to move along, but they wanted to shut down this airport,'' said police Maj. W.B. <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON>. `` This was an obvious attempt by the union to hurt the citizens of <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. We do n't like it, and we're not going to take it.'' Airport spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Braden </PERSON> said Friday was one of the busiest days in <ORGANIZATION> Hartsfield </ORGANIZATION>'s history, with about 140,000 travelers passing through the airport. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, about 300 Eastern strikers and supporters marched on Friday to <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> and blocked evening rush-hour traffic heading to the terminal of <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s sister airline. About 50 police wearing riot gear and holding night sticks tried to keep the crowd moving through the airport's roads, and an