<HEAD>Bush Calls for Renewed Effort on Civil Rights</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, marking the 25th anniversary of the Civil Rights Act of 1964, says he will be satisfied `` with nothing less than equality of opportunity for all Americans'' including 36 million who have disabilities. `` While celebrating our achievements and recommitting ourselves to their preservations, we must recognize that the full promise of the civil rights movement has still not been achieved,'' he told 200 civil rights leaders at a White House ceremony Friday. `` The hard lesson of the passing years is that it has not been enough to wage a war against the old forms of bigotry and inequality,'' the president said before flying off for a long holiday weekend in <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> called on <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> `` to join me in a new partnership to reauthorize the <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> with a goal of launching a renewed civil rights mission.'' The commission's six-year authorization expires Nov. 30. Civil rights leaders <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hooks </PERSON>, <PERSON> Vernon </PERSON> <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> and <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Farmer </PERSON> attended the ceremony. The landmark civil rights law was signed by President <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> on July 2, 1964. The act banned segregation in public accommodations and paved the way for court action to end bias in hiring and promotions. Also in the audience was <PERSON> Rosa </PERSON> <PERSON> Parks </PERSON>, whose defiant refusal to move to the back of a <LOCATION> Montgomery </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>, bus on Dec. 1, 1955, was an early milestone in the civil rights movement. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said the gathering was `` not only to commemorate an anniversary, but to celebrate a movement, and to rededicate our efforts to the unfinished work of that movement.'' However, some civil rights leaders say recent <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decisions restricting affirmative action and making it more difficult to prove discrimination in the workplace have hurt the civil rights movement. `` There was more damage done to civil rights statutes in the last 2 -LCB- weeks than in the last 2 -LCB- decades,'' said <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Neas </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Leadership </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> did not directly address civil rights leaders' concerns, but called for `` vigilant and aggressive enforcement'' of civil rights and said his administration wo n't tolerate discrimination. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> told reporters that justice had become `` more expensive, more distant and less likely to come'' because of the high court rulings. He said `` we need a meeting of some substance with the president to deal with legislative remedies to offset the impact'' of the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decisions. But some said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> seems more interested in defending the flag than the ideals the flag represents, alluding to his call for a constitutional amendment to outlaw desecration of the flag. `` So far they have put flag rights over workers' rights, over basic civil rights,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said after the ceremony. Attorney General <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> earlier this week that the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration wo n't pursue legislation to overturn the recent high court decisions affecting civil rights, preferring to wait until their impact can be assessed. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said economic barriers affect the lives of the disadvantaged as much as the remnants of legal discrimination. `` For that reason, I continue to support affirmative action and minority outreach programs,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` We will be satisfied with nothing less than equality of opportunity for all Americans _ and the removal of final barriers to self-reliance.''
