<HEAD>Grand Jurors Say They Were Held Back In Kennedy-Chappaquiddick Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Nearly 20 years after Sen. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s car plunged off the bridge at <LOCATION> Chappaquiddick </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, several grand jurors who investigated the accident have come forward to say the district attorney hindered their probe. One of the jurors, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Maciel </PERSON>, said Friday that there was a `` cover up'' in the case, but said he believed <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> was the victim, not the perpetrator. `` I think the man is innocent,'' <PERSON> Maciel </PERSON> said. `` I do n't believe <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> was driving that car. I think he took the blame for somebody else.'' <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Jo </PERSON> <PERSON> Kopechne </PERSON>, a 28-year-old secretary, was a passenger in <LOCATION> Kennedy </LOCATION>'s Oldsmobile when it skidded off Dike Bridge in <PERSON> Martha </PERSON>'s Vineyard on July 19, 1969 Trapped in the vehicle, she drowned in 8 feet of water in a tidal pond. The <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Democrat, who did not report the accident to police until 10 hours later, received a suspended sentence for leaving the scene. <PERSON> Maciel </PERSON> and the grand jury foreman, <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Leland </PERSON>, said former District Attorney <PERSON> Edmund </PERSON> <PERSON> Dinis </PERSON> prevented the 23-member jury from calling several key witnesses, including <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> and his cousin, <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Gargan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, because they had previously testified at an inquest. <PERSON> Leland </PERSON>, a 49-year-old pharmacist on <PERSON> Martha </PERSON>'s Vineyard, said <PERSON> Dinis </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Dukes </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> prosecutor, also refused to let the grand jury read the transcript of the inquest. `` When those two avenues were closed off, there was nothing for us to do really but go home,'' <PERSON> Leland </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Dinis </PERSON>, who is now in private practice in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bedford </LOCATION>, did not return telephone calls from The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> to his home and office Friday. He previously has denied stonewalling the investigation and has said there was not enough evidence to justify indicting <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> for manslaughter. <PERSON> Leland </PERSON> and <PERSON> Maciel </PERSON> said they have spoken out after two decades because they want the truth to come out and to clear the grand jury's name. `` I've lived with this thing for 20 years, and there have been all these innuendos that we were bought off,'' <PERSON> Leland </PERSON> said. `` The bottom line is, the grand jury tried its hardest to get to the truth, but we were not able to do our job.'' <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> has said he made a wrong turn that night and ended up on the narrow Dike Bridge. He also has said that he and a friend repeatedly dove to the car in unsuccessful rescue attempts, and that afterward he was `` exhausted and in a state of shock.'' <PERSON> Maciel </PERSON>, who owns a boatyard on <PERSON> Martha </PERSON>'s Vineyard, said he did not believe that <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, a frequent visitor to the island, would have made that wrong turn. He said he did not know why <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> would have taken the blame for someone else, `` unless it was someone very young.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bedford </ORGANIZATION> also reported Friday that several other jurors have backed statements by <PERSON> Leland </PERSON> criticizing the investigation. `` It was a coverup,'' said <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Mayhew </PERSON>, a grand juror now living in <LOCATION> Matta