lenders are responsible for about 20 percent of the loss while <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> picks up the tab for the remaining 80 percent. <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> now faces more than $ 100 million in claims against bad loans made in the program, said Rep. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Lantos </PERSON>, D-Calif., subcommittee chairman In the most recent audit in March 1989, <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> found the <ORGANIZATION> Benton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Knoxville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, had misrepresented mortgage amounts and rents on 14 projects it had underwritten, creating an estimated $ 22 million in excessive mortgages, said <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>. He said the government would pay excessive subsidies of $ 37 million over the 15-year period of contracts for rental housing <PERSON> Benton </PERSON> had coinsured. <PERSON> Benton </PERSON> is one of three companies which has been placed on six months' probation from the program. Three companies have been suspended and three others are under review by <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> revealed Friday that <PERSON> Benton </PERSON> is the subject of a grand jury investigation, which he said he would not discuss. <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> said his first report of problems in the coinsurance program was sent to then-Assistant Secretary of Housing <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON>, one of several former <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> employees who was paid as a consultant on projects funded under the moderate rehabilitation program. Rep. <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON>, D-Conn., observed that `` <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON> used <PERSON> Benton </PERSON> in all of his deals,'' in that program Meanwhile, congressional pressure is mounting for a complete review of the housing department. One staffer said <