<HEAD>Drug Maker Says Product Safe Despite Lack of Full Test</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> pharmaceutical company says its employees appear to have won government approval for one of the firm's generic drugs for treating high blood pressure by substituting the brandname product for its own in comparison tests. `` It would appear that that is the case,'' <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Vitarine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pharmaceuticals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gardens </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, said Friday. <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> said he believes the company's drug, which has been recalled, is safe. A congressman, however, said the case raises questions about the drug's safety as well as the government's drug approval process. The drug is a generic Dyazide, a widely prescribed treatment for high blood pressure. <ORGANIZATION> SmithKline </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beckman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> developed Dyazide and marketed it for 20 years before the first generic version was approved two years ago. <ORGANIZATION> Vitarine </ORGANIZATION> was approved in February 1988. <ORGANIZATION> Vitarine </ORGANIZATION> recalled its product a month ago. At least three employees have been suspended, the company said. However, <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> said, preliminary results of a just-completed comparison study measuring the rate and extent of absorption of the two drugs shows that <ORGANIZATION> Vitarine </ORGANIZATION>'s product falls within an `` acceptable range.'' `` <ORGANIZATION> Vitarine </ORGANIZATION> has no reason to expect any safety or efficacy problems with this product. <ORGANIZATION> Vitarine </ORGANIZATION> has produced millions of dosage units since the product was first introduced in February 1988 and as of this date has received only six adverse experience reports,'' he said. <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> declined to elaborate on the findings of the company's internal investigation, except to confirm that the company told the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> it suspected Dyazide was substituted for <ORGANIZATION> Vitarine </ORGANIZATION>'s product in comparison tests As a result, Dyazide would have been tested against only another sample of Dyazide. The chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> investigations subcommittee, which brought the possibility to public light Thursday, said the case raises questions about how the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> approves generic drugs. `` Events suggest that we can no longer be assured that the products tested are the products marketed,'' said Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>, D-Mich., subcommittee chairman `` That such a simple but apparently effective fraud could have gone undetected raises some serious new questions about the safety and efficacy of these drugs, and about the law,'' he said. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> acknowledged that it is investigating the company, but spokesman <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Nesbit </PERSON> said he could n't comment on the inquiry or address the safety of the <ORGANIZATION> Vitarine </ORGANIZATION> drug. An <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> source, who spoke on the condition of anonymity, said the agency doubted the generic version was unsafe because it had undergone other tests and no problems with people using it had been reported.
