<SECOND>PM-Abortion Consent, Bjt,0626</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Overturns Law Requiring Parental Consent for Abortions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CONNIE CASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 State attorneys say they will fight a judge's decision to overturn a law requiring parental consent for abortions performed on minors in a case that could be affected by a long-awaited <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling. The parental consent law, passed by the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> in 1988, was to have taken effect today, two days before the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> was expected to announce action on a <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> law seeking to limit legalized abortion. `` The statute's vagueness can be expected to have a substantial chilling effect upon a minor's right to obtain an abortion,'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> said Friday in a ruling made after about an hour of oral arguments. The national Planned Parenthood Federation and the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tennessee </ORGANIZATION> challenged the law, seeking a preliminary injunction blocking its enforcement if the issue had not been decided Friday. Deputy Attorney General <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Catalano </PERSON> said the state will consider an appeal to the 6th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> after reviewing <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>'s opinion. ` It's our contention that the statute is constitutional,'' he said. `` We intend to pursue the case to that end.'' <PERSON> Catalano </PERSON> also said the case could be affected by an upcoming ruling from the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on a <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> law that restricts the availability of abortions and defines life as beginning at conception. The justices could rule Monday or order another round of arguments, delaying the decision until next year. `` If they rule, we'll read it with interest,'' <PERSON> Catalano </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON> <PERSON> Ray </PERSON>, executive director of <ORGANIZATION> Tennessee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Volunteers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION>, said his citizens' group, which lobbied for the 1988 legislation, may ask the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> to pass a new version of the parental consent law next year. The law would have made it a misdemeanor for a doctor to perform an abortion on a girl under age 18 without obtaining written permission from both her parents or her legal guardian. The statute allows exceptions, however, if the parents are divorced; if the pregnant girl wins a court waiver of the consent requirement; or if one parent can not be found `` within a reasonable time and manner.'' `` The phrase ` reasonable time and manner' is so vague as to fail to give the physician notice as to when his actions will violate the statute and subject him to criminal sanctions,'' the judge said. That violates the doctor's right to due process under the 14th Amendment, he said. <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> said uncertainty about the law's meaning would lead doctors to protect themselves by denying abortions to minors who ca n't locate one of their parents `` The judge ruled on every single ground on which we alleged the law was unconstitutional,'' said <PERSON> Dara </PERSON> <PERSON> Klassel </PERSON>, attorney for Planned Parenthood. Two cases pending before the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> involve parental consent laws in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> abortion law generally requires doctors to notify a parent before performing an abortion on a young, unmarried girl. Passed by the state <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> in 1985, the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> law never took effect due to a successful legal challenge by an <LOCATION> Akron </LOCATION> abortion clinic and one of its doctors. The <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> law requires some girls to tell both parents at least 48 hours before having an abortion. A federal appeals court upheld the law, but postponed its ruling's effect while the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> reviewed it. According to court papers, parental notification or consent laws are in effect in <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>. A challenge to a <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> parental consent law is under consideration by that state's <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>.
