e. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> also was hooked up to a resirator and other life-support equipment, <PERSON> Tiwanak </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> suffered liver failure Wednesday, and suffered heart, lung and kidney failure in May. He has remained in the hospital since being admitted Jan. 15. One of <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' doctors, who spoke on the condition of anonymity, said the exiled leader's condition has generally worsened over the past five months. `` It's like a stair step,'' the doctor said. `` He gets worse, levels off, gets worse and levels offs, but sooner or later he'll fall off the steps. Another doctor, also speaking on the condition of anonymity, called <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' survival remarkable. `` He really does have a tremendous will to live,'' the doctor said. `` I can honestly say that just about any other person in his condition would have been dead months ago. There's no real explanation.'' The Marcoses were indicted in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> last year on federal racketeering charges. They stand accused of stealing more than $ 100 million from their homeland to buy art and real estate in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' illness has led him to be separated from the case. Mrs. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> is free on $ 5 million bail. The couple fled here in 1986 when a popular revolt swept <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> into the presidency. She has refused <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' many requests for permission to return home.
