<SECOND>PM-Lenin Library, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0436,0732</SECOND>
<HEAD>Virginia Company Computerizing Lenin Library In Moscow</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `Chachra's company..', to UPDATE with name of
library director; picks up 5th graf, `The work...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID REED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLACKSBURG, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet citizens looking for books at the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> library where <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON>, <PERSON> Dostoyevsky </PERSON> and <PERSON> Chekhov </PERSON> once studied will soon be using computers programmed at a <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> university. <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tech </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Library </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Vinod </PERSON> <PERSON> Chachra </PERSON> sees it as more than a technical challenge to computerize the card catologue of the massive <ORGANIZATION> Lenin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Library </ORGANIZATION>. The project will encourage the Soviet policy of openness, or glasnost, and help further business relations between the superpowers, he says. `` This is really opening up access to information,'' <PERSON> Chachra </PERSON> said. `` In one sense, this is bringing in more equality with the technology. By automating the system, it greatly increases the access to all people.'' <PERSON> Chachra </PERSON>'s company, which is controlled by a non-profit arm of <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tech </ORGANIZATION>, announced last month that the Soviets had chosen its software system to automate their national library. <PERSON> Chachra </PERSON> will meet with the library's director, <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> Semyonovich </PERSON> <PERSON> Kartashov </PERSON>, in <LOCATION> Blacksburg </LOCATION> on July 18 to discuss the start of the project in November. The work is expected to take up to four years and cost $ 1 million, he said. The <ORGANIZATION> Lenin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Library </ORGANIZATION>, located just off <LOCATION> Red </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION>, has 35 million books in 247 languages and 3,000 employees. Its 18 reading rooms, many of them with ornate, high ceilings and lit by chandeliers, seat more than 2,300 people and are visited by more than 7,000 readers each day. In comparison, the <ORGANIZATION> Library </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> has 26 million books and the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Library </ORGANIZATION> has 6 million books, <PERSON> Chachra </PERSON> said. The library was founded in 1862 as the <LOCATION> Rumiantsev </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Library </LOCATION>, named after a count whose collection accounted for most of its original holdings. It was renamed in 1925 after the father of the Russian revolution. In addition to <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON>, famous Russians who have studied in the library include authors <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> <PERSON> Tolstoy </PERSON>, <PERSON> Fyodor </PERSON> <PERSON> Dostoyevsky </PERSON> and <PERSON> Anton </PERSON> <PERSON> Chekhov </PERSON>. <PERSON> Chachra </PERSON> visited the library during a recent five-day trip to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. `` I was struck by the number of people waiting outside the door for the library to open,'' he said. `` There are n't that many libraries in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The users are dedicated.'' They have to be. Checking out a book is a lengthy and frustrating process, and just finding the right card catalog file is an ordeal because there are separate catalogs for various subcollections, <PERSON> Chachra </PERSON> said. After finding the right catalogue, the user must write the title and author on a slip of paper and stand in line for up to an hour to give the note to a circulation clerk. The clerk sends the note to the book retrieval area via pneumatic tubes. `` It can take anywhere from a half a day to five days to get a book,'' <PERSON> Chachra </PERSON> said. `` Occasionally, the book has been lent to someone else, and after waiting that long you find out you ca n't get it anyway.'' Under the planned automated system, people looking for a book will step up to a U.S.-made computer running on software designed by <PERSON> Chachra </PERSON> and his staff. For many, it will be their first experience with a personal computer, <PERSON> Chachra </PERSON> said. Users will be able to make a book request directly from a terminal and find out right away whether the book is checked out, <PERSON> Chachra </PERSON> said. The current system restricts access to information because of its cumbersome nature, <PERSON> Chachra </PERSON> said, but that will change. `` By the nature of the technology, it will be in favor of the user,'' he said. `` The software is designed for open access.'' <PERSON> Chachra </PERSON> said it remains to be seen whether <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> officials will give access to some books that are now off limits to users, presumably for political reasons. The <ORGANIZATION> Lenin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Library </ORGANIZATION> will be the first Soviet library to computerize, but it will be the sixth national library to automate with software from <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tech </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Library </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION>. The company has computerized the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gallery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Library </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Library </ORGANIZATION> in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, as well as libraries in <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION>. The company has computerized nearly 100 other libraries, including that of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
