<HEAD>Passengers Balk at Reboarding Problem-Filled Flight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EDMONTON, Alberta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hundreds of vacationers on a trip from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> endured hours of delay, a malfunction that forced their plane to dump its fuel, an unscheduled stop and a fire on their bus. Hot under the collar, 53 of them finally just said `` no'' and refused to head for home Friday night on the same chartered plane that spilled its fuel into the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> earlier this week. `` I value my life more than I want to get on that plane,'' said <PERSON> Joanna </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris-Brown </PERSON>, a travel consultant from <LOCATION> Liberpool </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. She was among 480 passengers on the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747 that dumped fuel en route back to <LOCATION> Manchester </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, and landed Thursday night at the <ORGANIZATION> Edmonton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airport </ORGANIZATION> after a loss of oil pressure in the engines. On their way to the flight home Friday night, their bus caught fire. A passing fire truck put out the blaze, which was blamed on a leak of power-steering fluid. The mishap was another in a series of incidents and inconveniences to plague the passengers from the moment they began their trip two weeks ago. Before leaving <LOCATION> Manchester </LOCATION>, they were delayed more than an hour. They waited 16 hours to board in <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> on the return flight. After the oil pressure problem forced the plane down, the passengers once again waited five hours because they were told customs officials had not arrived. Many were openly hostile when a representative for the British consulate broke the news Friday night they would be leaving on the same plane. `` It's been repaired four times by competent