<DATELINE>DEN HELDER, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The humble mussel, a tidal water delicacy, is now playing a pivotal role in monitoring pollution in the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>. Spread over 15 locations along the Dutch coast, 1,500 of the jet-black mollusks were put into service this week as a way scientists can check the flow of poisonous waste through the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>, one of the most heavily polluted basins in the world, a project spokesman said Friday. In filtering algae from sea water for food, the bivalves also store poisonous waste and heavy metals. A look at what they have stored gives a picture of the quality of water they live in. `` They give us a perfect overview of the water quality over the time span involved,'' said <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Scholten </PERSON>, a spokesman for the government project. The mussels live in plastic baskets attached to shipping buoys up to six miles off the coast. They will be checked in three six-week periods over a year at a cost of $ 113,600. `` Mussels are ideal for this kind of job because they filter so much water,'' <PERSON> Scholten </PERSON> said. The average mussel processes about 13 gallons of sea water a day, he said.
