<TEXT>
 Industries with the highest stakes in clean air legislation are lobbying to make sure stringent enforcement provisions are n't slipped into the formal bill submitted to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> by the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration. Industry lobbyists say they believe some <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> officials want to be tougher on industry than does President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who unveiled his clean air plan June 12. Lobbyists for the auto, electric utility and petroleum industries say they are particularly concerned about tougher standards on acid rain, additional curbs on motor vehicle pollution, and the amount of flexibility that industry will be given to reduce pollutants. The bill promises to be at the center of a major congressional struggle for at least the next six months. `` We're emphasizing the importance of sticking with the president's program,'' said <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Brooks </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> lobbyist who has participated in petroleum industry meetings with administration officials since <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> outlined his plan. `` If they start dragging in cats and dogs ... it will slow down the process considerably,'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> responded: `` If the rumor is we're going off in directions rejected by the -LRB- administration's -RRB- Domestic Policy Council, that's absolutely false We're taking a very conservative approach to making the president's idea work.'' The industry lobbyists said their concern was inspired in part by an early <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> draft of the legislation, which contained measures industry did n't like, but which preceded <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s announcement and is now _ everyone agrees _ outdated. They added that administration officials listened, but made no specific commitments on legislative language. The industry executives pointed out that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> only revealed the broad outlines and goals of his plan, while leaving the legislative drafting _ where a word or numerical change can make an enormous difference _ to technical and policy experts. `` Our concern is the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> will try to make the bill more stringent than <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> indicated,'' said one lobbyist for a large utility who participated in one meeting and was familiar with several others. `` I would say the effort is low-key, fairly targeted and fairly discreet.'' The lobbyist, who spoke only on condition his name not be used, said utilities are concerned with the acid rain reduction plan because <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> did not use precise language on the amount of sulfur dioxide emissions to be permitted by coal-fired power plants. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said his proposal `` envisions'' an emission standard of 2.5 pounds per million BTUs through 1995. That would be tightened to `` approximately'' 1.2 pounds per million BTUs through the year 2000. `` Those words give <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> room to wiggle around'' in achieving the sought-after 10 million-ton sulfur dioxide reduction, the lobbyist said, noting that <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> has in the past discussed an even tougher standard for the 1995-2000 phase. The industry official added that at a meeting with <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> officials, `` We did n't accuse them of subverting what the president said, but <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> knew why were were inquiring about some of these things.'' The auto industry, which says the replacement of old cars with new ones will lower motor vehicle emissions, is wary of new tailpipe standards. The petroleum industry is concerned about how far <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s plan for alternative motor vehicle fuels will go Other industry concerns are that <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> might try to impose strong permit requirements that would be a `` bureaucratic nightmare,'' insert strong federal authority over state and local governments and give the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> administrator wider powers. There has been no comparable lobbying effort by environmental organizations, said <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> <PERSON> Padgett </PERSON>, director of Environmental Action. `` Trying to lobby <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> would be trying to lobby our friends,'' <PERSON> Padgett </PERSON> said. `` And we do n't have the access to <ORGANIZATION> OMB </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- Office of Management and Budget -RRB- that industry does.'' <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Ayres </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Clean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION> composed of major environmental groups, said he's willing to wait for the `` fine print'' before launching any lobbying campaign. One oil industry lobbyist said, however, he thinks <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will keep his proposal free from tampering. `` This president is hands-on'' and `` he's going to want to see it and understand it,'' said <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Himmelstein </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>.
