<FIRST>r i AM-Burma-China     07-01 0717</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Burma-China,0737</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students Draw Parallels Between China, Burma Protests</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRUNNSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANERPLAW, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For <LOCATION> Burmese </LOCATION> students who saw their own dreams of democracy crushed last year, the suppression of pro-democracy demonstrators in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> conjures up bitter memories. Several thousand protesters were killed in <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> when the military put down a nationwide uprising demanding political reform and an end to a quarter century of economic mismanagement and authoritarian, one-party rule. `` We feel for the Chinese students because the same things have happened to us,'' said <PERSON> Aung </PERSON> <PERSON> Myint </PERSON>, who was a university student during the <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> uprising. `` It seems that there is n't much difference between the military in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and the military in <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>.'' Unlike `` people power'' struggles in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> and elsewhere in <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, force has largely succeeded, at least for the time being, in stifling popular cries for democracy in <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. But nine months after <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> put down its uprising, the political climate remains uncertain. Elections have been promised in the spring of 1990 and oppostion parties have been permitted. But the opposition groups complain of harrassment and continuing arrests, and many doubt the military will be willing to transfer power in the future. `` What we saw in both countries was a challenge to established authority in a form that they were not willing to countenance,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Leifer </PERSON> a <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> expert in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. He said a common factor in both countries, which seemed to lead to the bloody climaxes, was an older generation of leaders controlling the events. <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> expert <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Silverstein </PERSON> notes differences between the top leaders of the two countries. `` <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON> was a whole lot smarter and -LRB- <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s -RRB- Ne Win a whole lot crueler,'' the American academic said in an interview, noting <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s economic progress and <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s stagnation. Although Brig. Gen. <PERSON> Saw </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> is nominally <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s head of state, Western diplomats say 78-year-old strongman Ne Win retains power, despite his official retirement last July. In <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, no promise of political change has been indicated. But both countries have pledged to pursue domestic economic reforms and open doors to foreign economic influence, which in <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s case had been closed since the early 1960s. The international community was outraged by both crackdowns and announced economic sanctions. But within a few months the boycott of <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> began to erode. Critics say the revival of trade ties, mostly by <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> countries, has boosted the military government and works against the democratic movement. If maintained, international economic sanctions were likely to be more damaging to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s more sophisticated economy, <PERSON> Leifer </PERSON> said. Years of socialist mismanagement took <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>, once one of <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>'s richest countries, to the brink of economic collapse. <PERSON> Silverstein </PERSON> believes it was because of this that <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s uprising attracted great popular support. He believes the <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> `` revolution'' was on the verge of success until the military became worried about splits within its ranks. Only then did it move decisively to crush the demonstrators. Some differences were also reported within the Chinese military, but if they existed they were finally overridden. In <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>, students like <PERSON> Aung </PERSON> <PERSON> Myint </PERSON> are last year's heroes. While Chinese dissidents are feted in the West and allowed generous visa extensions, <LOCATION> Burmese </LOCATION> students complain they are largely ignored. <PERSON> Aung </PERSON> <PERSON> Myint </PERSON> was among the estimated 7,500 students who fled the repression. He said he decided to go after witnessing the killing of five close friends and many others at the gates of <ORGANIZATION> Mandalay </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Univerity </ORGANIZATION>. He now lives at <LOCATION> Manerplaw </LOCATION>, the jungle headquarters of the <ORGANIZATION> Karen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, an ethnic rebel group fighting for greater autonomy. Several hundred <LOCATION> Burmese </LOCATION> students are fighting alongside the rebels. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> congressmen last week voted $ 2 million in humanitarian aid to the exiled Burmese, many of whom suffer harsh jungle conditions and have contracted malaria. The students say more could be done for them and against the <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> government by the international community. <PERSON> Silverstein </PERSON> said the political climate in <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> is more volatile than in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, `` I do n't think for a moment there has been any settling down, the heavy hand of the military has squashed but not eliminated,'' he said. `` I think ... that while <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> has found his man and the system will go forward. Ne Win has still to find his man and his system.''
