 Three Kurdish guerillas were killed Saturday in a clash with security forces, the semi-official <ORGANIZATION> Anatolia </ORGANIZATION> news agency reported. The agency said the security forces were conducting a search in a mountainous area near the Syrian border when they encountered the guerrillas and ordered them to surrender. The rebels opened fire, the agency said. Security forces have launched a massive operation in the mountains of southeastern <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> as a result of the increase of Kurdish attacks over the past two months. Kurdish rebels are fighting for an independent Marxist state in parts of eastern and southeastern <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>. More than 900 security personnel and civilians and an equal number of insurgents have been killed since the Kurds started hit-and-run attacks in 1984, official reports say. Ethnic Kurds make up about one-fifth of <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>'s population of 55 million.
