<HEAD>HUD Contractors Held Millions Owed Government but Agency Rarely Noticed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, his wife and his attorney gave up trying to audit the accounts he held as a private closing agent in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> for the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION>, the government decided to take a crack at it. When <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> auditors finished the math, they said <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> owed the government more than $ 1.6 million for the period 1984-1987 but had only half that in the separate accounts he was required to keep for proceeds from the sale of single-family homes for the agency. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>'s story is like dozens of others, tales that together show an agency with little control over its private agents and even less control over its own accounting for the hundreds of millions of dollars the agents handle. In <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>'s case, the auditors decided $ 839,812 was missing from accounts. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>'s attorney protested, reminding the auditors they had spent time at <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>'s home and should be well aware of his `` modest lifestyle and extremely modest financial base.'' The attorney, <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Novy </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, said in a letter December 1987 to <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> that <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> could no longer afford to pay for legal services and that the government's efforts to trace the money `` are fruitless.'' The government disagrees, and is trying to recover the money plus interest in a $ 7.5 million civil suit. Audits of closing agents in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Buffalo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> and elsewhere produced similar findings: most of the agents were sending <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> its money late; some were n't sending it at all. <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>, already strapped for funds because of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration cutbacks, was losing millions of dollars a year in interest. `` Delays by closing agents in remitting sales proceeds cost <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> over $ 16 million in fiscal year 1987,'' the agency's inspector general's office concluded after a nationwide audit of <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>'s sales and acquisitions of single-family homes, one of numerous agency programs. The same report said records for the single-family program had discrepancies involving 38,000 properties and $ 834 million dollars. The inspector general's report, and related audits of closing agents in several areas of the country, were obtained under the Freedom of Information Act. They are receiving close scrutiny by law enforcement officials and members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> as part of investigations in <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> mismanagement and influence-peddling during the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> years. The documents show closing agents, although required to wire <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> its money within a day of completing a sale, routinely held the money, in almost all cases at first for a few extra days and then, as the mounting indiscretions went unnoticed, for longer periods _ weeks then months and in many cases two or more years. `` During a 31-month period, the escrow company remitted $ 109 million of sales proceeds to <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> an average of 47 days late,'' a <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> audit found. `` The delays cost <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> $ 1.1 million in lost potential interest income.'' That company, <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Escrow Co. of <LOCATION> Downey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, made just one of the 1,576 payments it handled over the nearly three-year period on time; some were up to 258 days late, <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> records show. The owner claimed he did not know about the payment deadline; <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> records show it was listed in his contract with the agency and had on other occasions explicitly discussed it with the company. <PERSON> Melvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Parsons </PERSON>, president of the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Escrow, said in a telephone interview that the company disputed the findings of the audit but settled the case last year for $ 250,000. `` It was cheaper for us to settle it than to go into court,'' he said Thursday. A review of 37 cases in <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, found that late payments cost the government more than $ 18,000. In <LOCATION> Buffalo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, an audit of a onetime <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> broker found that he withheld payments, overbilled and paid himself advances from <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> money. When he died two years ago he was almost $ 73,000 in arrears to the government, and his widow later withdrew money from a <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> escrow account, according to department records. She has agreed to repay the money, <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> officials say. In <LOCATION> Montgomery </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>, auditors said <PERSON> Rick </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Lind-Davis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Real </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Estate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> failed to pay <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> $ 2 million and was late in remitting an additional $ 3.8 million from sales between August 1984 to November 1987, costing the government more than $ 320,000 in interest. Federal authorities still are trying to recover that money, according to <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> officials. Some of the agents mingled <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> money with private and other checking accounts, conceivably earning interest that should have been going to the government, according to documents. <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> was not detecting the late payments because of sloppy or nonexistent record-keeping. Some office kept records on index cards; others had so few computers that workers had to go from the first floor to the ninth of a regional <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> office to use one. Many offices accepted slips requesting wire time to transfer money to <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> instead of actual transmittal receipts from closing agents _ many of whom never actually transferred the funds, the documents show.
