<HEAD>New Chinese Leader Could Face Insurmountable Problems</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEJ13</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> <PERSON> Zemin </PERSON> was named head of the world's largest communist <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, he inherited more than a powerful position _ he inherited a load of serious problems <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON>, successor to the disgraced <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziyang </PERSON>, must deal with the aftermath of the government's suppression of the pro-democracy movement and with an economy slipping out of control. He also must live in the shadow of his two successors, the late <PERSON> Hu </PERSON> <PERSON> Yaobang </PERSON> and <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON>, both purged for failing to clamp down on the democratic impulses of youth. <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON>'s political future seems to rest on the health of 84-year-old senior leader <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON> and the desires of other party elders who strongly believe in the communist ideology that has ruled <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> for 40 years. `` It depends, as so much has in the last weeks, on what one old man decides to do. That's where it becomes unpredictable, because it's one old man,'' said an <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> diplomat who spoke on condition of anonymity. <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> already is being compared to <PERSON> Hua </PERSON> <PERSON> Guofeng </PERSON>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s titular head during the transitional years of political instability between the 1976 death of <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> <PERSON> Tse-tung </PERSON> and the rise of <PERSON> Deng </PERSON>. There probably will not be more pro-democracy demonstrations in the near future like the one crushed when soldiers drove thousands of protesters from <LOCATION> Tiananmen </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> on June 3-4. But the willingness of people to put up with political repression may be tied to how well the economy performs and to living standards. Premier <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Peng </PERSON> last fall announced a two-year austerity plan designed to slow economic growth to curb inflation, running about 30 percent in urban areas. Industry was growing so quickly that it was taxing raw material and energy supplies. Also, banks were issuing loans for new construction and expansion without getting old loans back, adding to the inflationary pressures. <PERSON> Li </PERSON>'s plan has had modest success. The industrial growth rate has been shaved from about 20 percent last year to 11 percent, and inflation has dropped slightly. But factories ca n't pay their bills because credit has dried up, and exporters are reneging on contracts because they lack the raw materials needed for production. A deepening energy crisis is forcing factories to shut down for days each week, and severe shortages of some raw materials have contributed to rampant corruption. Factories often have to pay off officials who obtain materials at low state-set prices and resell them for handsome profits. Unemployment, which according to official estimates will rise to 3 percent from 2 percent this year, has caused great social despair. Millions of people, mostly peasants from the countryside, have been put out of work by the cancellation of construction projects and have been left to drift from town to town looking for work. Premier <PERSON> Li </PERSON>'s economic measures have all but stopped economic reforms, particularly changes crucial to bringing prices in line with market values and easing serious supply-demand gaps. The purge of <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON>, one of the pioneers of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s market-oriented reforms, and his followers will deprive the nation of some of its most innovative economists. `` Economic thinkers will at best be under a cloud,'' said a <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> diplomat who spoke on condition of anonymity. `` There will be a lot less intellectual energy.'' Diplomats also speculated that <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> will, like Premier <PERSON> Li </PERSON>, be more comfortable with central planning models that <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> tried to dismantle. That would not bode well for flagging efforts to restructure <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s economic base. In the first three months of 1989, before students took to the streets to demand political reforms, 22 percent of state-run enterprises lost money. The amount of losses, made up by the state treasury, was the equivalent of $ 1 billion, up 120 percent from the same period in 1988. Foreign businessmen who fled when the crackdown began now are returning, but the political turmoil could seriously affect <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s foreign business relations The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> says a travel advisory urging businessmen and tourists to stay away from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> remains in effect. One embassy official said safety concerns continue and cited a recent incident in which troops fired into the air when a car driven by an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> businessman backfired as it pulled away from a military checkpoint. <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON>, who worked to attract foreign investment to the city of <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>, where he was party chief before his promotion, may have been picked by <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> partly to reassure the outside world that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> will keep its doors open to the West. But new foreign investment, which <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> badly needs for its modernization drive, likely has been severely hurt by the crackdown. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> have urged international lending institutes to postpone new loans to protest the crackdown. Such a move would deprive <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> of billions of dollars in development money. <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> has deferred consideration of $ 780 million in loans. Tourism also has been seriously hurt, cutting deeply into earnings of more than $ 2 billion a year that have helped <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> solve its chronic foreign exchange problems.
