 Fireflies are big game to some hunters here and one group has made flashy profits from the incandescent insects. <PERSON> Dorothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> and her army of net-wielding firefly hunters swarm the area nightly for the luminous bugs, which fetch a penny apiece from a <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> chemical company. The lightning bug season, which began last month, is `` really getting pretty doggone good right now,'' Ms. <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> said. Ms. <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, 62, leads about 100 members of the <ORGANIZATION> Firefly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Princeton </ORGANIZATION>, in north central Illinois, which is the largest of similar organizations in the state. Members range in age from 3 to 75. Two years ago the club netted 600,000 lightning bugs, which brought $ 6,000 in profits, and by the end of last week it has caught 33,000 fireflies this summer, bringing in $ 330. It's not uncommon for firefly hunters to make $ 5 every evening in about 20 minutes, Ms. <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> said. `` It makes good spending money for them,'' she said. `` And at the same time, it's being done for a good purpose.'' Ms. <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> sends the captured fireflies to the <ORGANIZATION> Sigma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>. The company removes the section of the insect containing luciferin and luciferase, chemicals which have hundreds of medical and scientific uses, including detection of cancer cells.
