<FIRST>u a AM-AbortionOpponents 1stLd-Writethru a0526 07-01 0764</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion Opponents, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0526,0779</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abortion Foes Gearing Up For New Battleground _ War In States</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS penultimate graf to CORRECT name to Hucks sted Huck.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON COHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Anti-abortion activists anxiously awaiting a possible <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision Monday on abortion rights are gearing up for what they see as the next phase of their campaign _ war in the states. The National Right to <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, which was winding up its three-day convention here Saturday, is hopeful the high court will, at the very least, return authority to the states to decide whether to restrict abortion. If that happens, there's a realistic expectation that <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>, probably <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> and possibly <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> could be among the first states to consider abortion curbs, said <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> <PERSON> Balch </PERSON>, the committee's state legislative coordinator. State action on abortion laws would depend on various issues, including timing _ many legislatures do n't convene again until 1990 or 1991. `` What we're talking about is an extremely long, hard struggle here,'' <PERSON> Balch </PERSON> said. A <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> case, <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> vs. Reproductive Health Services, is pending before the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> and a decision is expected Monday. Missouri's law puts restrictions on abortions and defines life as beginning at conception. Upholding the <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> law, or even parts of it, could reverse or seriously erode the 1973 landmark decision, <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON>, legalizing abortion. Many abortion opponents here believe a total reversal of <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> is highly unlikely. But they feel this court is their best chance since 1973 to return the issue to local lawmakers and, thus, give abortion opponents the chance to advance their goals on a state-by-state basis. Restrictive steps that <PERSON> Balch </PERSON> said would be most likely to be introduced are parental consent and notification laws, and measures to give fathers a say in abortion decisions. A parental consent law that was to have taken effect Saturday in <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> was struck down Friday by a federal judge who declared the law unconstitutionally vague. Abortion foes say that if the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> upholds even part of the <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> law, it would be a victory and a signal to forge ahead. `` If it goes in any direction in our favor ... the first step you'll see is politically and legislatively a great push ... in all 50 states,'' said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Donnell </PERSON>, a Franciscan brother attending the convention. `` The pro-life movement is just going to move forward and intensify.'' `` This is phase II,'' he said. `` The first phase was 16 years ago,'' when <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> was decided. `` It's going to be a state fight, whatever happens,'' said <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> anti-abortion activist and an architect of the measure before the high court. Abortion opponents already are talking about special legislative sessions, petition drives and increased lobbying efforts. `` The legislators are feeling the faint heat coming down the pike and it's just getting hotter,'' said <PERSON> Brenda </PERSON> <PERSON> Hucks </PERSON>, director of <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION>. `` They're -LRB- also -RRB- going to feel heat from pro-abortion folks and the media. They'll be in the spotlight.'' Lawmakers `` have had some easy dodges,'' said <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Mall </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Iowa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Right </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> to </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. They'd say, `` ` Call me when we can start doing something.' Now, they're going to have to come out of the closet one way or another.'' The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Abortion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> said in a June report that both legislative houses in nine states _ <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> _ along with the city council in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, favor keeping abortion legal. The report also said 24 legislatures favor making abortion illegal and governors in 15 of those states support such actions. But abortion opponents wo n't make such distinctions. `` We're not counting any state as a loss,'' said <PERSON> Jacki </PERSON> <PERSON> Ragan </PERSON>, head of the committee's state organizational developmental department. `` We're not counting any state as a given. All will be battlegrounds. We're going to give it all we've got.'' They also say they're braced for the possibility of defeat _ but remain undaunted. `` We're not about to pack up and go away,'' Miss <PERSON> Hucks </PERSON> said. `` We're in it for the duration. It's more than a passing interest. It's a bone-deep commitment.'' `` It's our belief that whatever the result in the <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> case, that the decision in <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> is in fact doomed,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Bopp </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, the committee's general counsel. `` It is simply a question of when it will be reversed, whether it will be in this case or the next case or the next case. But it is inevitable.''
