ich thousands of union activists were interned. Solidarity was outlawed the following year. The communist party chief cited this association in the public eye as his reason for not wanting to be a candidate. <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON> helped crush Solidarity after martial law, but he won back confidence from the opposition by leading the government in negotiations that led to Solidarity's legalization and the elections for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>. The elections were the freest in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> since World War II and included opposition candidates for the first time.
