<HEAD>New York City May Become a Little Smaller</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s famed five boroughs could someday become four. The Legislature, working into early Saturday morning in an end-of-session marathon, voted to give <LOCATION> Staten </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> residents a chance to say whether they want to secede from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. If Gov. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> signs the bill, residents of the smallest borough might be able to vote in November 1990 on whether to take a bite out the Big Apple. <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> said Saturday he had n't decided what to do. Polls say <LOCATION> Staten </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> residents overwhelmingly favor secession, an issue tied up with a court-mandated restructuring of the largest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> city government. `` We did n't start out with the idea of leaving the city,'' said state Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Marchi </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Staten </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> Republican. `` We just wanted to maintain our voice in the city. We did n't have anything against the city of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. I ran for mayor there twice.'' The secession movement gathered steam after the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled in March that the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Estimate </ORGANIZATION>, which governs city spending and construction, was unconstitutional because it gave <LOCATION> Staten </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>'s 400,000 residents equal representation to the more populous boroughs, such as <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION>, with more than 2 million people. <LOCATION> Staten </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> residents fear the city charter revision commission's plan for revamping city government will shortchange their borough. `` It would reduce us really to colonial status,'' <PERSON> Marchi </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> said he believed the legislators' action was not an approval of secession, but simply a `` political statement. What they are saying is ` <LOCATION> Staten </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> ought to be protected.''' <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> said he shared those sympathies, but was n't sure how to go about providing such protection. <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> is from <LOCATION> Queens </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Bronx </LOCATION> are the other two boroughs. Residents of <LOCATION> Staten </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> have never considered themselves true <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> residents, said <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Connelly </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Staten </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> Democrat who shepherded the secession bill through the state Assembly. She noted, though, that the borough's more upstate character has lessened since the <LOCATION> Verrazano-Narrows </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bridge </LOCATION> linked it with <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> and it began absorbing people fleeing high housing costs and other urban woes in other boroughs. Many leaders from the other boroughs, including Mayor <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON>, a Manhattanite, fear the loss of tax revenue to the city if <LOCATION> Staten </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> secedes. Lawmakers who opposed the bill also argued that all <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> residents should have the right to decide if part of the city should break away. `` It's fundamentally unfair to all the other residents of the city of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> ...,'' said <PERSON> Assemblyman </PERSON> <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Genovesi </PERSON>, a powerful <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> Democrat. `` I do n't think that anyone has considered the ramification of how it all works out.'' <PERSON> Connelly </PERSON> argues that <LOCATION> Staten </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> residents never had a say in the 1898 decision by the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> that made the island a borough of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. The 1989 bill calls for <LOCATION> Staten </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> voters to decide two questions: whether <LOCATION> Staten </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> should break from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> and whether it should form a county or city type of government. The legislation wo n't allow a secession vote unless a charter revision is voted on in a citywide referendum this November. Even if the secession decision is a long way off and by no means a certainty, it's already unifying a borough that's been the butt of jokes, <PERSON> Marchi </PERSON> said. `` There is a lot of excitement,'' he said. `` I'm telling you, it does n't make any difference _ rich or poor, black or white, fat or skinny. It does n't make any difference.''
