nstitutional issue and therefore the plaintiffs can not prevail on the merits,'' said assistant attorney general <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Luinstra </PERSON>, who argued the case involved questions that should be challenged in a state court. But plaintiffs' lawyer <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Rappaport </PERSON> said the law deprives his clients of business without any rationale. `` There is a public interest in having children not smoke,'' he said. `` There's no public interest in having adults buying cigarettes hand-to-hand over the counter instead of having adults buy cigarettes from a machine after the business owner determines they are adults.'' Over the past week and before Friday's ruling, many of <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>'s vending machine companies were busy removing cigarette machines from restaurants, hotels and other public places in anticipation of the new law
