<HEAD>Technician's Death Turns Focus To Lab Research Safety</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS penultimate graf to CORRECT test results expected this
week, sted next week.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA PERLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MATTAWAN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Alsobrooks </PERSON> was hired as an animal technician at a research laboratory here, nobody told him the monkeys he'd handle likely would carry a virus that could kill him. Less than three months later, one of his co-workers is dead, a former co-worker is hospitalized and <PERSON> Alsobrooks </PERSON> and about 30 current or former colleagues are on an experimental anti-viral drug they hope will stem the rare disease in case they, too, have been infected. The herpes B virus, better known as the monkey virus, is found in more than 50 percent of rhesus monkeys, a type of macaque. The virus is harmless to the animals, but more than half of the 30 cases documented in humans since the disease was first reported 57 years ago have been fatal. It's commonly transmitted through bites and scratches. `` I try not to worry about things I have no control over, but my family is worried. My mother is lighting candles,'' said <PERSON> Alsobrooks </PERSON>, 33, whose blood test results were inconclusive. Thousands of these monkeys are being used daily in laboratory experiments nationwide. While progress is being made in the area of animal welfare rights, the conditions in which lab employees work are largely unregulated by federal or state law. Officials at <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> say they have complied strictly with guidelines set by the <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> and that the two technicians who were infected did not report their wounds. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> McGeorge </PERSON>, a 23-year-old technician, died June 20, just a few days after the virus was diagnosed. The hospitalized former employee, whose name is being withheld, is in serious condition. He worked at the company only one week before quitting this spring. Early detection was impossible since neither man reported his injuries, which is required by the company, said <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> X. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wazeter </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> IRDC </ORGANIZATION> vice president. When an employee reports being bitten or scratched by a monkey, a disinfectant is promptly applied to the wound to kill the virus, <PERSON> Wazeter </PERSON> said. Some employees said bites and scratches were so common and the pressure to complete studies so great that it was nearly impossible to report each wound to the company nurse. <PERSON> Wazeter </PERSON> denied there was pressure on employees to work fast and said reporting wounds is mandatory. He also denied allegations by several employees that the leather gloves used by monkey handlers _ part of the extensive protection gear _ usually had holes and took months to replace. The <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>'s guidelines, which are not enforced by any regulatory agency, were created two years ago after a herpes B outbreak in <LOCATION> Pensacola </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, killed two monkey handlers and infected two other people. Some current and former employees at the lab believe a high turnover rate, poor training, and heavy workloads played a part in the outbreak of the rare disease, which has been documented only 30 times since the first case was reported in 1932, said Dr. <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> epidemiologist. The disease, which attacks the brain and central nervous system, frequently leads to encephalitis, an inflammation of the brain, and then to death. Since the virus has been documented, 16 of the 24 patients who have shown symptoms have died, <PERSON> Holmes </PERSON> said. In one case in <LOCATION> Pensacola </LOCATION>, the virus was spread person-to-person. Of about 135 blood tests conducted on current and former <ORGANIZATION> IRDC </ORGANIZATION> lab employees who had contact with the monkeys in the last two months, 81 were negative and five were inconclusive, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> officials said. The rest of the results are expected this week. The company, which employs 350 people, does animal research for medical, pharmaceutical, veterinary and agricultural companies.
