<HEAD>Conservative-Leftist Alliance Forms Coalition Government</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 7-8 pvs, `The 62-year...' with 3 grafs to UPDATE
with some ministers announced Saturday night. Pick up 9th pvs, `The agreement...'
ADDS 1 graf background at bottom.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILIP DOPOULOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Conservative and communist parties ended a two-week political deadlock Saturday and agreed to form a coalition government. It was the first time communists have played a role in determining the formation of <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>'s government. It appeared, however, that the coalition would govern only three months and that its sole task would be to clean up <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>'s scandal-ridden political system The decision by the communist-dominated Coalition of the Left and Progress to join with the conservative <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> gave that party's premier-designate, <PERSON> Tzannis </PERSON> <PERSON> Tzannetakis </PERSON>, the support needed for a majority in the 300-member parliament. President <PERSON> Christos </PERSON> <PERSON> Sartzetakis </PERSON> announced that <PERSON> Tzannetakis </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION> parliamentarian since 1977, would be sworn in Sunday. In the June 18 general election, <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION> won 145 seats. The Coalition _ an alliance of the <ORGANIZATION> Greek </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, disenchanted socialists and the <ORGANIZATION> Eurocommunist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Greek </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Left </ORGANIZATION> _ won 28 places. Premier <PERSON> Andreas </PERSON> <PERSON> Papandreou </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Panhellenic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION>, or <ORGANIZATION> PASOK </ORGANIZATION>, lost after eight years in power, taking only 125 seats. Late Saturday night, the 62-year-old <PERSON> Tzannetakis </PERSON> announced the first of his Cabinet posts. Only two of those he appointed _ the justice and interior ministers _ were non-parliamentarians affiliated with the leftist <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION>. Most others were from the New Democracy Party. Named as deputy foreign minister was <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Papoulias </PERSON>, currently the envoy in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. In negotiations leading up to the agreement, <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Constantine </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitsotakis </PERSON> had offered the Coalition the Justice and Interior ministries. The agreement came 40 years after the communists, in their bid to seize power, were defeated in a civil war by U.S.-backed government troops. <PERSON> Papandreou </PERSON>, 70, who was in a hospital for treatment of a heart and kidney condition, reacted bitterly to the pact between the two political forces. `` This alliance is without principles. It violates the popular will,'' he said. <PERSON> Papandreou </PERSON> had called on the Coalition to join <ORGANIZATION> PASOK </ORGANIZATION> so the two parties could set up a government. But Coalition leader <PERSON> Harilaos </PERSON> <PERSON> Florakis </PERSON> said he did n't want to be associated with a scandal-tainted group like the Socialists. A multimillion-dollar scandal allegedly involving key ministers in <PERSON> Papandreou </PERSON>'s government, and his open affair with a woman half his age while he was married, contributed to <PERSON> Papandreou </PERSON>'s downfall. <PERSON> Mitsotakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Florakis </PERSON> agreed that their coalition would have a three-month life span and that its work would be limited to restoring democratic institutions and cleaning up Greek politics. <PERSON> Florakis </PERSON> said at the end of the three months, `` we will re-examine our position and act accordingly.'' But because of the wide gap in the two sides' political ideologies, it appeared unlikely the coalition could survive after its task of purging former <ORGANIZATION> PASOK </ORGANIZATION> ministers and officials accused of involvement in scandals. If the coalition falls apart, the president will appoint a caretaker regime to lead the country to natonal elections. A newly elected government is needed to deal with pressing economic problems and complete negotiations with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> over the future of its four major military bases in <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>. The defense pact expired last December but a clause gives the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> 17 months to either close down the bases or renegotiate a new agreement. The two members of the new coalition differ over the presence of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bases. The Coalition has strongly opposed the four bases and called for their removal. But the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> favors negotiating a new agreement.
