If <PERSON> Ruffo </PERSON> _ a former mayor of <LOCATION> Ensenada </LOCATION> _ wins, the election would be the first gubernatorial race the <ORGANIZATION> Institutional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> lost in its 60-year history. <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Salazar </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s municipal committee in <LOCATION> Tijuana </LOCATION>, said Saturday he filed a complaint with the state election commission alleging that election officials were preparing to allow multiple voting with forged documents. Last week, the electoral commission burned 24,000 voting credentials, claiming many of them were falsified. Some people even use the registrations of deceased voters when they cast ballots. `` We can see if they are alive or dead. If they do n't come, they probably do n't exist,'' said <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> of the local electoral commission. Opposition officials say their members mysteriously disappear from the voting lists and are therefore unable to cast ballots. Hundreds of people waited all night Friday outside one election office to obtain their registration cards. <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON> <PERSON> Amaral </PERSON> <PERSON> Munoz </PERSON> said the wait was worth it. `` I'm worried about the political situation in this country,'' he said. `` What's most important is that we decide through popular vote. Who wins must do so honestly.'' <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON> <PERSON> Morales </PERSON> <PERSON> Munoz </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> campaign committee in <LOCATION> Tijuana </LOCATION>, said 8,000 people still were not registered by Saturday. But <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> of the electoral commission said: `` We'll work up until the last minute so people can vote.'' <PERSON> Lu