<HEAD>Early Airmail Flier Dead At 99</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEARWATER, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Alva </PERSON> <PERSON> Sole </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airmail </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> pioneer who delivered mail to <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON> and was a friend of World War I ace <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Rickenbacker </PERSON>, died at age 99. Sole died in his sleep Thursday. In air mail's infancy, Sole would swoop down, aim his canvas-covered biplane at two posts on the ground, fly between them and snatch a mail pouch from a wire stretched overhead before climbing back into the air. Highlights of Sole's career included flying mail to <LOCATION> Roosevelt </LOCATION> at Warm Springs, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>, and taking <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON>'s son, <PERSON> Elliott </PERSON>, on plane rides. He flew planes with <PERSON> Will </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON>. His friends included <PERSON> Rickenbacker </PERSON>, <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s top World War I ace and <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>' founder, <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Doolittle </PERSON>, the World War II flier who led a daring surprise attack on <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> in April 1942, and war correspondent <PERSON> Ernie </PERSON> <PERSON> Pyle </PERSON>. Sole was born in Wheeling, <LOCATION> W. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, in 1889 and as a teen-ager went to work shoveling coal on a train He landed a job as a mail clerk on a train and worked his way up to become head of the postal service's <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> office in 1933. In the meantime, he obtained his pilot's license, and volunteered for some of the first airmail flights in the late 1920s and early 1930s. Many of the pilots died, getting lost in fog until their fuel ran out or crashing into mountains. Their most dangerous maneuver was the pickup, when they would swing down between the posts.
