tion, he said. The building is managed by <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> suburb of <LOCATION> Torrance </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Komsky </PERSON>, vice president of the company, said an investigation would begin into the fire, but he would not comment on the lack of sprinklers. <PERSON> Komsky </PERSON> said the company is `` shocked beyond words at the loss of life and the injuries.'' Six federal agencies have offices in the building, located north of midtown <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, including the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION>, Department of the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>. None of those offices is on the sixth floor, where the damage was the worst and where the people were trapped, <PERSON> Perrin </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Perrin </PERSON> said he hoped the fire would result in legislation requiring sprinkler systems in all buildings beyond a certain height, regardless of their ages. He said he planned to send information about the blaze to congressmen interested in fire safety issues. There were reports by some agencies Friday that a fifth person had died in the fire, but <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said that stemmed from confusion over the unrelated death of a construction worker who fell from a construction site a few miles away, at about the same time as the fire.
