<HEAD>Antiwar Bomber Joins '60s Activists Reunion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A man whose antiwar bomb shattered a five-story campus building said he regrets the 1970 blast killed someone but still feels he was right to protest the Vietnam War. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fine </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wisconsin </ORGANIZATION> student at the time, was among veterans of the 1960s protest movement who gathered this weekend for a reunion. He and three other men were put on the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>'s list of most-wanted fugitives after their homemade bomb damaged a campus building, killing a student and injuring several other people on Aug. 24, 1970. Several other people were injured. Fine, <PERSON> Karleton </PERSON> <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON> and his brother, <PERSON> Dwight </PERSON> <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON>, were eventually arrested and received prison sentences. <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> <PERSON> Burt </PERSON>, identified as the fourth participant, was never captured. The building had formerly housed the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mathematics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> and was frequently a target of campus antiwar demonstrations. Fine and other participants denied intending to harm anyone. `` Regardless of why the bombing happened and the feelings people had about the center and the war in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, that in no way justifies the death and destruction,'' Fine said in an interview published Saturday. `` So I have a lot of regrets about that. Always have, always will, I'm sure,'' he said. Weekend events included discussion groups with topics ranging from Women in the 1990s to the Decline and Fall of Civil Rights. Fine, 37, who works in a law office in <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>, said he worried about what kind of reception he would get in Madison. `` I'm not going to come back and attempt to justify things I was convicted of which were very tragic,'' he said. `` I probably would n't contemplate doing something like that now under the same circumstances,'' <PERSON> Karleton </PERSON> <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON> said. `` But for where I was at and where people were at the time, I thought it was right.'' The Madison native said he had no plans to attend the reunion but would be on the campus selling fruit juice from a stand he has operated for several years. <PERSON> Dwight </PERSON> <PERSON> Armtstrong </PERSON> is in prison in <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> on a drug charge. Madison <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agent <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Frazer </PERSON> said <PERSON> Burt </PERSON> was dropped from the most-wanted list years ago but remains a federal fugitive. Asked if authorities would watch for <PERSON> Burt </PERSON> during the reunion, university security chief <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON> said: `` I'm looking for him. I do n't expect him to show up.
