<HEAD>Moslems Demand Repatriation to Pakistan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of Pakistanis stranded in <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION> since it broke from <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> 17 years ago demonstrated Saturday to demand repatriation. Witnesses said 5,000 Urdu-speaking Moslems attended the rally outside the Central Secretariat, the seat of government. The protesters, many carrying placards reading `` we want to go to <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>,'' dispersed after they were blocked by riot police from entering the secretariat. <PERSON> Nasim </PERSON> <PERSON> Khan </PERSON>, a leader of the nearly 250,000 Pakistanis awaiting repatriation, said `` if our demand is not met soon, we will march via <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> to reach <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>.'' <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION>, a Bengali-speaking nation, is separated from <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> by 870 miles of Indian territory. <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION> was the eastern wing of Urdu-speaking <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> when it was formed in 1947 after gaining independence from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. It broke away from <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> after a 1971 war. About 500,000 Urdu-speaking Moslems migrated in 1947 to <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, as <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION> was then known, but after the war demanded that they be sent to <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. In the first phase of repatriation under a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Refugees </ORGANIZATION> program about 250,000 were sent back, but the program was halted when funding ran out. The remaining migrants live in disease - and crime-ridden shanty communities set up in most cities in <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION> A Jeddah-based charitable organization, <PERSON> Rabita-e-Alam-e-Islami </PERSON>, is trying to raise $ 300 million