<HEAD>Charles Kimbrough Says `Murphy Brown' Character Really a Romantic</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Dial </PERSON>, the rigid, humorless anchorman on <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION>' `` <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>,'' is really a romantic at heart. `` The public side that he's developed is armor-plated,'' says <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Kimbrough </PERSON>, who ought to know. He plays the co-anchor on the show's fictional TV newsmagazine `` F.Y.I.,'' which also features <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Candice </PERSON> <PERSON> Bergen </PERSON> -RRB-, <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Fontana </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Regalbuto </PERSON> -RRB- and <PERSON> Corky </PERSON> <PERSON> Sherwood </PERSON> -LRB- Faith Ford -RRB-. `` Inside he's a dreamer. He probably grew up reading <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Halliburton </PERSON>'s travel adventures and wanting to be just like <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Murrow </PERSON>. He seems older because his values are those of an older time. It makes him uncomfortable to have to share the show with a former beauty queen like <PERSON> Corky </PERSON> <PERSON> Sherwood </PERSON>. `` He seems gruff with no sense of humor. But he can loosen up with his friends. ... The comedy comes from the fact that he's such a stiff. I have a fondness for that part of him that's loving and vulnerable.'' The thing <PERSON> Kimbrough </PERSON> says he dreads most is the comparison of Dial to <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Baxter </PERSON> on `` The <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> Show.'' `` <PERSON> Jim </PERSON>'s a good journalist. <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Baxter </PERSON> was a very bad journalist. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON>'s a smart guy, <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> was pretty dumb.'' The role is the first real television exposure for <PERSON> Kimbrough </PERSON>. He has spent most of his acting career on the stage in regional and repertory companies, and got his `` big break'' with his Broadway debut in `` Cop-Out.'' He also was in `` Company'' and `` Sunday in the Park with <PERSON> George </PERSON>.'' `` I was mostly working in the theater and making money doing commercials. I'd occasionally do a movie or a part on television. When I was asked to do an audition tape for ` <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>' I figured it was just a ticket to oblivion. You sit in front of a camera and they put a bright light in your face. `` I loved the script and I wanted to do it. After the audition tape I walked in the rain, feeling very depressed. Three weeks later they asked me to fly to <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. I found out I was competing against one of my best friends. They put us up in the same hotel and we laughed about it. We both wanted it a lot. I flew back to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and was doing a commercial on location in <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> when they called and said I had the part.'' <PERSON> Kimbrough </PERSON> grew up in the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> area, where his only early connection with the theater was an aunt, <PERSON> Emily </PERSON> <PERSON> Kimbrough </PERSON>, who with <PERSON> Cornelia </PERSON> <PERSON> Otis </PERSON> <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> wrote `` Our Hearts Were Young and Gay.'' The book about two young women traveling in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> was adapted for the stage, and was made into a movie in 1944. `` I grew up listening to music and doing a lot of drawing and painting. I went to <ORGANIZATION> Indiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> _ and I've never told this to anyone _ because they had a great opera department. I thought it would be wonderful to go to a school where I could go to the opera on Saturday night. `` I tried out for a school play and got a part. My grade average went from a ` B' to a ` C' overnight because I was closing the pizzeria every night with people who liked what I liked. `` I was in a lot of plays but it was too scary to call myself an actor. When I went to the <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drama </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> I took directing instead, but I spent most of my time acting.'' <PERSON> Kimbrough </PERSON> met his wife, <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, at <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION>. After graduating they landed roles in `` All in Love,'' a musical adaptation of <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheridan </PERSON>'s `` The Rivals.'' `` I was making Equity scale and taking home $ 37.32. <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> was non-Equity and took home $ 10 a week. They paid us in cash so it seemed like more. After that we got out of the business for a while.'' <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> taught college and <PERSON> Kimbrough </PERSON> worked at a record club, but they both returned to the stage in the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> version of a Julius Monk revue. That was followed by three years with the <ORGANIZATION> Hartford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and six in <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION>. Despite directing classes at <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Kimbrough </PERSON> says he has n't spent much time in that capacity. `` I directed a few plays but I hated to be the unpopular one in the company. If you tell an actor what to do I'd always worry about it.''
