<FIRST>a f BC-Fireworks-China Adv03   07-01 1147</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Fireworks-China, Adv 03,1181</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday, July 3</HEAD>
<HEAD>Fireworks Booming For Now but Future Supplies Could Fizzle</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 While millions of Americans twirl sparklers, set off firecrackers and ooh and aah over Fourth of July fireworks displays, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> importers are getting headaches worrying about future festivities. `` There certainly is considerable concern for the 1990 season,'' says <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Conkling </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pyrotechnics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. `` Everybody is awaiting word from factories in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> about the status of future deliveries.'' So, before the last wisp of smoke has cleared on July 4, many fireworks firms will have placed next year's orders in anticipation of a possible shortage due to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s precarious political and economic situation. The Chinese, credited with inventing fireworks about 1,000 years ago, make the bulk _ more than 75 percent _ of the stuff <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> consumers use during Independence Day celebrations. Giving people such fleeting thrills as they get from lighting Roman candles takes <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies months of planning, negotiating and waiting for shipments _ even in the best of circumstances <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> fireworks firms normally have their overseas ordering done by the autumn of each year to allow enough time for foreign factories to manufacture and ship the goods early enough for distribution in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> before July. Now, however, the uncertainty of Chinese supplies has companies scrambling to keep from being caught short next Fourth of July, by far the biggest time of year for the fireworks business. Current supplies should be enough to satisfy this season's demand; most imported Chinese fireworks had already arrived in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> or left <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s shores before the <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> government's bloody crackdown on pro-democracy `` The shipments for this year started arriving in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> back in November of 1988,'' observed <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON>, a fireworks expert at the Consumer Product <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. `` So the majority of them were already here or on the water.'' <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Grucci </PERSON>, a member of the family that runs one of the country's biggest organizers of fireworks shows, says intermediaries that handle his company's purchases abroad have advised <PERSON> Grucci </PERSON> not to panic. Nonetheless, the <LOCATION> Bellport </LOCATION>, N.Y.-based Fireworks by <ORGANIZATION> Grucci </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> expects a slowdown in Chinese production. `` We've already placed our purchase orders -LRB- to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> -RRB- now to try to beat the rush,'' <PERSON> Grucci </PERSON> said. `` We usually do n't make big orders until August or September to overseas.'' Firms like <PERSON> Grucci </PERSON> that specialize in aerial displays do n't rely on <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> as much as companies do that primarily provide fireworks for consumer use. Besides what it imports from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Grucci </PERSON> supplements its own products with fireworks from numerous foreign sources including <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> and other Far Eastern countries as well as ones in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Royce </PERSON> <PERSON> Trout </PERSON>, of <ORGANIZATION> Atlas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprises </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, a fireworks maker and importer that ships throughout the country, says manufacturing in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s northern provinces is more likely to be affected by political unrest than factories elsewhere in the country. This is because most of the turmoil seems to have flared up around <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s economically developed areas and educational centers, he says. Potential production snarls wo n't hit all types of fireworks. Factories assembling firecrackers, a highly labor-intensive task, mainly are located in the more rural part of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s southern provinces so firecracker shipments are n't likely to be disrupted, says Trout. Adding to problems that might arise from developments on the political front, <PERSON> Trout </PERSON> says he's been informed that several Chinese factories are facing financial trouble. A lack of credit to cover material and other costs has put three or four factories in <LOCATION> Hunan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Province </LOCATION> in danger of closing. The southeastern province annually accounts for about 15 percent of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s total fireworks shipments to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which came to more than 50 million pounds in 1987, the most recent year for which <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government figures were available. Tightness in availability of one of <ORGANIZATION> Atlas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprises </ORGANIZATION>' most popular items probably reflects these financial difficulties. The item is a type of ground spinner _ a category of fireworks that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> created _ that spews fiery blossoms as it gyrates on the ground. Ground spinners are tubes packed with a an assortment of fireworks producing multiple effects. `` I'm very, very worried about what kind of supply we'll get from some provinces both from a political standpoint and a financial standpoint,'' says Trout. People in the fireworks business say there are only a few countries that could help fill a potential shortfall in Chinese shipments. And, there are limits to how much places such as <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Macao </LOCATION>, the Portuguese-administered territory off <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s southeastern coast, could compensate. <PERSON> Conkling </PERSON> of the pyrotechnics trade group says fireworks are an important export for <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. The country was becoming a powerful force in fireworks just before former President <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> reopened trade with the country in the early 1970s. It has come to dominate the industry today, largely because its factories turn out products of acceptable quality at unbeatable prices due to low labor costs. `` Fireworks is a legitmate science in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> _ universities do research into pyrotechnics and fireworks and this translates into big business for the country,'' says <PERSON> Conkling </PERSON>. For years, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has kept fireworks prices down, very close to the cost of production, to attract customers. But <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> businesses say that even before the political problems they were told to expect price hikes of 15 percent to 30 percent for next season's orders as the Chinese try to eke out more profit. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> retail sales of fireworks will total about $ 200 million this year, the industry says. Government figures indicate <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> supplies about 76 percent by weight of all fireworks brought into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> but the industry says the figures probably understate Chinese imports. As <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s shipments have grown, the quality has been slipping, possibly because newer factories are n't as familiar with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> regulations. All imported fireworks must meet the same safety standards as domestically made products. Trout, who also is president of the industry's trade association, says the group has been working on a sort of self-regulatory program to promote consistent quality, partly to account for advances in fireworks since government regulations were written. Because of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s trade dominance, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industry has been taking special care to see that the Chinese know what's expected of them. The industry is preparing an improved translation into Chinese of all the requirements, set down by several <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> agencies. As part of the quality campaign, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industry representatives had scheduled a trip to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> in late July and early August. Now the campaign may have to be put on hold. `` We are quite concerned at this point as to how the situation in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> will affect our efforts to get this quality assurance program in place,'' said <PERSON> Conkling </PERSON>. The meeting in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, he says, `` is very much up in the air at this point.''
</TEXT>
