<FIRST>a f AM-BusinessMirror Adv04   07-01 0733</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Business Mirror, Adv 04,0753</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv04</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release AMs Tuesday, July 4</HEAD>
<HEAD>Is There Anything Good About A Recession?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Recessions, or economic downturns of the kind Wall Street is now worrying about, have a terrible and well-deserved reputation. But is there anything nice to be said about them? Lots. They remove excesses like severe inventory pileups from the economy. They remind sellers that the consumer is still boss. They might even be accompanied by or cause lower prices and borrowing rates. What they do best, perhaps, is remind both sellers and buyers that the old law of supply and demand is still on the books. In boom times the seller usually has the upper hand; in bad times, the consumer ascends. This pervasive impact may have shown up already in lower housing and stock prices. And it could make even bigger inroads into the automobile market, which for a year has been fighting its own private battle with a slowdown. The automotive market, in fact, has been a display case of the strategies that come into play when the demand-supply balance is changing. Demand for cars has been ebbing for at least a year. Supply, however, has remained high. Under such conditions the suppliers must make concessions, which they did in the form of rebates and below-market borrowing rates. While the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> attempted to ease the economy into a slower pace by raising borrowing rates, the automakers sought to challenge them by lowering their own rates. It was a battle the automakers were destined to lose, because the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> had the ultimate power; it had the option of raising rates until it won its way. The automakers, in contrast, could lower their rates to zero, but not beyond. Conceding defeat, the automakers have sharply reduced production in an attempt to restore seller-buyer balance. Scheduled output for July is at an annual rate of 5 million units, or roughly half the annual selling rate. The question now is whether the balance can be restored in time to avoid price cutting. If demand remains low, the possibility exists that companies may be unable to reduce inventories sufficiently before new models are announced. If so, more automobile bargains might be available. Consumers will have won. Over the past year housing has also demonstrated the power of supply and demand. Demand was down, due to high prices and interest rates. In response, and despite a recent and probably temporary upturn, prices stagnated or fell. A housing market of that sort is a warning to makers of appliances, furniture and other items associated with housing, such as lawn products, to lower their inventories or else be forced to lower their prices. If a recession does develop, and there is still no proof that one will, there could other consumer benefits. Credit card issuers, for example, have clung to high interest rates, some of them charging more than 20 percent, preferring instead to attract customers through contests, low-cost merchandise, travel discounts and the like. However, such incentives lose their drawing power when people are in a recession mode, waiting and watching their dollars. The biggest incentive in such an atmosphere might be lower interest charges. Sellers of nonessential purchases might be forced to win customers through price cuts. Among them are airlines, resorts, hotels, various entertainment outlets and restaurants, all of which have been raising prices. Eating out, for example, already has suffered a hit, as economist <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Yardeni </PERSON> points out. From 1982 to 1987, restaurant meal sales rose from $ 112.9 billion a year to $ 133.4 billion a year. They peaked at a $ 139 billion rate in January of this year; by May the rate was down 14 percent to $ 132 billion. When restaurateurs see figures such as these, they know what must be done _ cut prices. True, they have the option of dramatically improving the quality of food and service. But in a recession, price cuts are much better. Price cuts are nice, but not the recession that produces them. Most people, it seems safe to say without a survey, would opt for expansion and pay raises instead. That leads to the ultimate good thing to be said about a recession: It is the base for the next expansion, for more jobs, higher pay and lots of spending options.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv AMs Tuesday, July 4</NOTE>
