<FIRST>a f BC-CreditMarkets Adv03 1stLd-Writethru 07-01 0796</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Credit Markets, Adv03, 1st Ld-Writethru,0825</SECOND>
<HEAD>adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday, July 3</HEAD>
<HEAD>Junk-Bond Mutual Funds: Tempting, But Dangerous For The Uninformed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 15th graf, Vanguard has ..., to CORRECT April figure and
percentage change for Vanguard fund.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BART ZIEGLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Investors have been pouring money into junk-bond mutual funds in recent months as interest rates available elsewhere have fallen, but they may be unaware of the danger lurking in these tempting, high-yield investments. `` Many people hear the word ` bonds' and they think ` safe, conservative,''' said <PERSON> Neal </PERSON> <PERSON> Litvack </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Fidelity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investments </ORGANIZATION>, operator of one of the largest junk-bond funds. `` Junk bonds have a tendency to dance to a different drummer.'' That drummer is the state of the economy. Unlike investment-grade corporate bonds, junk bonds face a greater danger of plummeting in price in a recession. Junk bonds are bonds that carry a low credit rating as determined by credit-rating agencies. Their low rating reflects the fact that the companies that issued the bonds may be deep in debt or otherwise poor credit risks. Junk bonds also are used to raise cash for many leveraged takeovers, where the corporate raider takes on a great deal of debt in order to pay for the target company. In contrast, investment-grade corporate bonds are considered a conservative, safe investment because the issuing company is rated financially sound and considered able to meet its debt obligations even in a downturn. To make up for their extra risk, junk bonds pay a higher interest rate. Junk bond mutual funds have been yielding 12 percent or more recently, compared with about 9 percent for investment-grade bond funds and 8 percent for <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bond funds. <PERSON> Litvack </PERSON> said the assets of <ORGANIZATION> Fidelity </ORGANIZATION>'s junk-bond mutual fund surged from $ 1.7 billion at the end of March to about $ 2 billion last week. While most investment companies would be happy to see their investment funds grow, Boston-based <ORGANIZATION> Fidelity </ORGANIZATION> is concerned. It believes many of the new investors _ some of whom pulled money out of other, safer <ORGANIZATION> Fidelity </ORGANIZATION> mutual funds _ do n't know what they're getting into `` Right now there is a misperception about what drives the performance of these securities,'' said <PERSON> Litvack </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Fidelity </ORGANIZATION>'s vice president of marketing. `` Interest rates are not the primary driver of these funds; it's much more a function of the economy.'' With investment-grade bonds, declining interest rates usually lead to higher bond prices. That's because bonds keep paying the same fixed interest while rates available elsewhere are becoming less attractive. But junk-bond traders are more concerned about the financial health of the companies that issued the bonds. If the economy sours, these companies would be at risk of not earning enough to pay the interest on the bonds, or even of outright default. `` A lot of these -LRB- junk -RRB- bonds have n't been tested in a down market,'' said <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mattes </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Vanguard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, another major mutual-fund operator. `` There could be a stampede out of the fund in a recession,'' he said. `` There will be a lot of people running for the door at the same time. In fact, the price may go down more because of that.'' <ORGANIZATION> Vanguard </ORGANIZATION> has seen the assets of its junk-bond fund grow 13 percent in the past two months, from about $ 1.14 billion at the end of April to about $ 1.29 billion last week. Some is from appreciation and the rest from new investors. <PERSON> Mattes </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Vanguard </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Forge </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, sent brochures to its customers to warn them of the risks of its junk-bond fund. `` It should not be viewed as a short-term investment at all,'' he said. Long-term investors would be at a lesser risk of losing principal because they could ride out an economic downturn. Investors expecting declining interest rates should put their money in <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> funds, <PERSON> Litvack </PERSON> said. In fact, total return on <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bonds _ the total interest paid plus any change in the bond prices _ exceeded that of the higher-yielding junk bonds in the first five months of this year. The January-May return on seven-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bonds exceeded 6 percent, while <ORGANIZATION> Fidelity </ORGANIZATION>'s junk-bond fund returned only 2.26 percent and <ORGANIZATION> Vanguard </ORGANIZATION>'s returned 2.12 percent due to major declines in the price of these bonds as the economy slowed, according to <ORGANIZATION> Lipper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Analytical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Litvack </PERSON> said junk-bond funds are not for investors saving for retirement or other needs One major mutual-fund company, <ORGANIZATION> Dreyfus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, said it is so concerned about the risks of junk-bond funds that it does n't sponsor one. `` The underlying basis for junk bonds is that economic expansion will continue forever, enabling highly leveraged companies to meet their heavy debt burdens,'' said <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Stein </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Dreyfus </ORGANIZATION>' chairman and chief executive. Dreyfus, he said, is not that optimistic.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
