<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, July 1-2, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Coffee Prices Percolate Amid Jitters Over Price Support Pact</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with settlement prices and other action
Friday.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Fear that discord among the world's major coffee producers will spark a collapse of the market's 26-year-old price-support machinery kept the coffee futures market on edge this past week. Traders' caffeine jitters were tempered late in the week by hopes that members of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coffee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> will find a way to avert a crisis. On other markets, precious metals slumped but ended the week on a strong note; energy prices see-sawed in volatile trading; wheat started strong but dipped by week's end; corn and soybean prices were mostly stronger; and meat and livestock prices were mixed. The latest signal of hope in the coffee market, unconfirmed reports that the ICO may decide to postpone a vote on whether to extend the agreement with some sort of price-support mechanism in place, sent prices soaring Friday at <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Coffee, <ORGANIZATION> Sugar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Cocoa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. The current six-year price-support deal is due to expire Sept. 30, and member nations of the <ORGANIZATION> ICO </ORGANIZATION>, composed of 74 major coffee producers and consumers, are at odds over proposals for a new agreement. Members of the <ORGANIZATION> ICO </ORGANIZATION> are scheduled to vote Monday on two price-support proposals. One would extend the existing agreement as is, with no change in quotas. The other calls for extension with changes that would increase the availability of mild arabica coffees _ one of the most popular varieties. Adding to the confusion is a recommendation from the <ORGANIZATION> ICO </ORGANIZATION>'s executive board to extend the pact for two years, but to abolish its price-stabilizing quota machinery The result would leave coffee prices after Sept. 30 subject to free-market forces for the first time since 1963. The board, which met Thursday and Friday, also called for an <ORGANIZATION> ICO </ORGANIZATION> vote on immediate suspension of the quota system if it rejects the two proposals, as some analysts have predicted it will do. The executive board acts merely as an advisory group, and the full ICO is not bound by its recommendation. `` It's a very nervous market simply because it is being pushed around by these very contradictory statements,'' <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevenson </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said Friday. `` Prices have been extremely erratic,'' he said. The reports that the ICO may postpone the vote for several weeks was considered bullish `` because it would imply that if they do, then the producers and the consumers will have more time to reach a compromise,'' <PERSON> Stevenson </PERSON> said. But the week opened on a bearish note, with reports that <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, the world's second largest coffee producer, would move to abolish all export quotas unless the <ORGANIZATION> ICO </ORGANIZATION> can agree on one of the two proposals. That sent coffee futures prices plunging 1.63 cents to 6.05 cents Monday, with the July contract at $ 1.11 a pound _ the market's lowest close since Aug. 2, 1988 But they rebounded Wednesday on vague hopes for a solution, and again on Friday, settling .50 cent to 3.25 cents higher, with the July contract at $ 1.1137 a pound.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Precious Metals</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Gold, silver and platinum prices started their slide early in the week at <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> on the strength of the dollar, falling sharply later on further signs that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy is heading for a recession. But the dollar's weakening Friday added a firm tone to the market.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Energy</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Crude oil started the week with a bang at the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> on continued concerns about supply and technical factors. Heating oil and gasoline also started the week higher, but gas prices plunged Wednesday after the release of the weekly <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> report showing an increase in refinery activity. Energy prices rebounded Thursday, but gas prices closed lower on Friday.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Grains</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Heavy buying in the wheat pit at the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> was sparked by anticipation of major purchases of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat by the Soviets. But by Friday a forecast for good harvesting conditions put pressure on the wheat market, while a revised, dry forecast in corn and soybean growing regions sparked a rally in those pits.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Livestock and Meat</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Prices opened the week strong at the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> but became mixed as traders awaited Friday's quarterly hogs and pigs report from the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION>. Here are some commodity price trends for the past week: Wheat for delivery in July settled Friday at $ 3.97 \ a bushel, down slightly from $ 3.97 -LCB- a week earlier; July corn rose to $ 2.66 -RCB- a bushel from $ 2.62; July oats fell to $ 1.49 -LCB- from $ 1.52 -LCB-; and July soybeans increased to $ 7.35 a bushel from $ 7.31 Live cattle for delivery in August settled at 70.15 cents a pound, up from 69.87 cents last Friday; August feeder cattle dipped to 80.87 cents a pound from 81.12 cents a week earlier; July hogs fell to 48.67 cents a pound from 49.67 cents; and July pork bellies rallied to 35.85 cents a pound from 33.67 cents. Gold for delivery in August fell to $ 377.30 a troy ounce from $ 381.80 while July silver settled at $ 5.155 a troy ounce, down from $ 5.338. August crude oil rose to $ 20.27 a barrel from $ 19.71 a week earlier; July heating oil fell to 49.35 cents a gallon from 49.49 cents; and unleaded gasoline for delivery in July settled at 59.91 cents a gallon, down from 62.92 cents.
</TEXT>
